                <h1>Welcome to week 1 </h1>
                <br />
                <p>
                    Welcome to the Mindfulness Based Stress Reduction (MBSR) Course.
                    The following  contains information and exercises to support you through the course.  Things often become clearer the more we practise.
                    The practice documents are for you to make personal notes about your experiences and you are invited to do so as part of the course as it allows you to consider your journey.   Be as honest as you can. The notes you make are not to be shared (unless you wish to), they are for you to explore and reflect.
                    You may experience some deeper emotions during your practice, if this happens it is quite natural and nothing to be afraid of.   We can discuss these in class or on a one to one before or after the session.  If you wish to discuss anything that is connected to mindfulness practice between sessions then you can contact me by email or we can arrange a time to talk.
                    I look forward to exploring mindfulness with you and hope that you find this a rewarding and therapeutic experience. It may even become a way of living.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Home practice is an important part of the course
                </p>
                <p>
                    The patterns of the mind that we will be working on to adapt have often been around for a long time. These patterns are often habitual and automatic. We can only expect to succeed in making changes in these long established ways of the mind if we put time and effort into learning new ways.

                    It can be challenging to find the time to devote to home practice, but it is worth it.  A useful attitude to adopt is ‘I’ll give it my best shot, and keep and open mind. At the end of the course I will decide what I have learned and what to take away.’  In order to make a decision about whether this approach could be a useful part of your life you need to engage with it fully during the 8 weeks.

                    A part of each session will be to reflect on your experiences of the home practice during the week. We will also discuss any difficulties that arise for you during the practice.  Much learning of the course can be drawn from these experiences.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Facing difficulties
                </p>
                <p>
                    A central aim of the approach is to learn how to be more fully aware and present in each moment. The good news is that this makes life more enjoyable, interesting, vivid and fulfilling.  However, it also means facing what is present, even when it is unpleasant and difficult.  During the practice you will find that turning to face and acknowledge difficulties is, in the long run, the most effective way of reducing unhappiness.  In this course you will learn gentle ways to face difficulties and will be supported whilst doing so.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Patience and persistence
                </p>
                <p>
                    Working to adapt established patterns of the mind means investing considerable time and effort, the effects of which may only become apparent later.  In many ways, it is much like gardening; we have to prepare the ground, plant the seeds and ensure the seeds have the nourishment to grow, and wait patiently for the results.   The invitation is therefore to approaching the course with gentle patience and persistence.

                </p>
                <p>

                    Warmest wishes,
                    <br />
                    Jean
